00:33:04.940 --> 00:33:06.940
What I wanted to show you
is how messy this data

00:33:06.940 --> 00:33:08.480
is, to be very frank.

00:33:08.480 --> 00:33:11.000
So we're trying to observe
these incredibly faint objects

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:13.050
in the distant universe,
and as a result,

00:33:13.050 --> 00:33:15.320
there's at least two big
challenges that we face.

00:33:15.320 --> 00:33:17.900
One is that each individual
observation is noisy.

00:33:17.900 --> 00:33:19.760
And two, we don't
get as complete

00:33:19.760 --> 00:33:21.110
a data set as we'd like to have.

00:33:21.110 --> 00:33:24.050
We only really get a few
observations of each exploding

00:33:24.050 --> 00:33:26.930
star, and just the few weeks
that it's bright on the sky

00:33:26.930 --> 00:33:29.210
before it fades into obscurity.

00:33:29.210 --> 00:33:31.820
And that's a huge challenge from
a statistical point of view.

00:33:31.820 --> 00:33:33.362
It means we really
need to treat each

00:33:33.362 --> 00:33:35.653
and every single one of these
observations as something

00:33:35.653 --> 00:33:36.290
truly precious.

00:33:36.290 --> 00:33:37.956
There's an enormous
amount of investment

00:33:37.956 --> 00:33:40.250
to the scientific
community in dollars

00:33:40.250 --> 00:33:41.770
and building these
telescopes to be

00:33:41.770 --> 00:33:44.030
able to collect these
precious few data points.

00:33:44.030 --> 00:33:45.980
So it is my mission, the
mission of our group,

00:33:45.980 --> 00:33:47.956
to use statistical
modeling to extract

00:33:47.956 --> 00:33:49.580
every last piece of
information that we

00:33:49.580 --> 00:33:52.730
can from these relatively
few precious data points.

00:33:52.730 --> 00:33:54.920
And what we do with that
is understand the physics

00:33:54.920 --> 00:33:56.400
of supernova explosions.

00:33:56.400 --> 00:33:58.250
So we relate the
observational parameters

00:33:58.250 --> 00:34:00.560
that we measure from
these limited observations

00:34:00.560 --> 00:34:01.950
of these explosions.

00:34:01.950 --> 00:34:03.440
So for example, on
the x-axis here,

00:34:03.440 --> 00:34:04.950
the total duration of the event.

00:34:04.950 --> 00:34:06.860
How long it stays
bright in the sky.

00:34:06.860 --> 00:34:08.929
On the y-axis, how bright it is.

00:34:08.929 --> 00:34:11.000
We relate those
observational parameters

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:13.520
to the theoretical parameters
of different types of stars

00:34:13.520 --> 00:34:15.110
and the explosions they produce.

00:34:15.110 --> 00:34:17.614
So other astronomers actually
explode stars and computers,

00:34:17.614 --> 00:34:19.280
and they figure out
