00:37:25.850 --> 00:37:27.410
that I think of
this through, which

00:37:27.410 --> 00:37:29.474
is this duality between
inference and prediction.

00:37:29.474 --> 00:37:30.890
So the first thing
I'm going to do

00:37:30.890 --> 00:37:33.710
is make very explicit what
I mean by those terms,

00:37:33.710 --> 00:37:36.620
and I'll do that by introducing
this very generic concept

00:37:36.620 --> 00:37:39.710
of what is a mathematical
model or statistical model.

00:37:39.710 --> 00:37:42.930
So any statistical model is
a few fundamental components.

00:37:42.930 --> 00:37:45.920
There's some set of input data
that is fed into the model.

00:37:45.920 --> 00:37:48.770
Indicators that can be used
to predict other things.

00:37:48.770 --> 00:37:51.230
There are some outputs
from the model.

00:37:51.230 --> 00:37:54.890
Outcome data that we want
to understand and model.

00:37:54.890 --> 00:37:56.600
The way the model
goes from X to Y

00:37:56.600 --> 00:37:58.730
is by making predictions
by taking the input data

00:37:58.730 --> 00:38:01.592
and transforming it into an
estimate for the outcome Y.

00:38:01.592 --> 00:38:03.050
And the goal of
the model is really

00:38:03.050 --> 00:38:06.170
to do as good a job as possible
in making the predictions match

00:38:06.170 --> 00:38:08.597
the actual outcome data that's
used to train the model.

00:38:08.597 --> 00:38:11.180
And then importantly, there's a
set of parameters in the model

00:38:11.180 --> 00:38:12.440
that we'll call beta.

00:38:12.440 --> 00:38:14.030
And these parameters
are really how

00:38:14.030 --> 00:38:15.796
the model makes
predictions, and it's

00:38:15.796 --> 00:38:17.420
learning the values
of these parameters

00:38:17.420 --> 00:38:19.006
in the fitting
process that allows

00:38:19.006 --> 00:38:20.630
us to learn about
the actual mechanisms

00:38:20.630 --> 00:38:22.430
that we're trying
to model and study.

00:38:22.430 --> 00:38:24.860
And finally, there is
perception error in the model.

00:38:24.860 --> 00:38:27.479
There is some uncertainty
associated with it as well.

00:38:27.479 --> 00:38:29.770
So the next thing I'm going
to say is entirely obvious,

00:38:29.770 --> 00:38:31.250
but I'm going to
say it anyway, which

00:38:31.250 --> 00:38:33.208
is that there's that an
aspect of this modeling

00:38:33.208 --> 00:38:35.900
process that is critical in
both science and industry,

00:38:35.900 --> 00:38:37.110
and that's prediction.

00:38:37.110 --> 00:38:40.310
So the predictive aspect of
statistical models of course,

00:38:40.310 --> 00:38:43.010
is fundamental to
how data science is

00:38:43.010 --> 00:38:44.277
integrated into business.

00:38:44.277 --> 00:38:45.860
So I'll give you a
few examples of how

00:38:45.860 --> 00:38:47.780
this particular aspect
of the model prediction

00:38:47.780 --> 00:38:49.680
is very important.

00:38:49.680 --> 00:38:51.740
So in science for
example, if you're

00:38:51.740 --> 00:38:53.210
very interested
in exploding stars

00:38:53.210 --> 00:38:55.700
and you've observed supernovae
over the past few nights

00:38:55.700 --> 00:38:57.590
and you want to know what it's
going to do in the future,

00:38:57.590 --> 00:38:59.464
you might make a prediction
of the brightness

00:38:59.464 --> 00:39:01.169
of that exploding star tonight.

00:39:01.169 --> 00:39:03.710
What's it going to look like if
I try and observe it tonight?

00:39:03.710 --> 00:39:05.737
In an industry, particularly
in our industry,

00:39:05.737 --> 00:39:07.820
we're interested in people's
movie-going behaviors

00:39:07.820 --> 00:39:10.200
and we want to know whether
or not we might buy a ticket.

00:39:10.200 --> 00:39:11.240
So if there is
somebody that we have

00:39:11.240 --> 00:39:12.740
some information
about like, Alyssa,

00:39:12.740 --> 00:39:15.281
we might ask a question like,
is she going to go see a movie.

00:39:15.281 --> 00:39:17.930
- Not taking [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:17.930 --> 00:39:20.150
- I predict with 100%
confidence that Alyssa

00:39:20.150 --> 00:39:23.984
will see Pacific Rim Uprising
before it leaves theaters.

00:39:23.984 --> 00:39:27.331
[LAUGHTER] We'll
see if that's true.

00:39:27.331 --> 00:39:27.830
OK.

00:39:27.830 --> 00:39:29.990
So of course, we apply
predictive modeling

00:39:29.990 --> 00:39:31.940
all over the place in
our work at Legendary.

00:39:31.940 --> 00:39:33.830
I don't want to give
you an exhaustive survey

00:39:33.830 --> 00:39:35.930
of the broad set of research
that all the scientists that I

00:39:35.930 --> 00:39:37.550
showed you on the
earlier slide are doing,

00:39:37.550 --> 00:39:39.508
but I'll just give you
a scattering of examples

00:39:39.508 --> 00:39:40.800
in different categories.

00:39:40.800 --> 00:39:43.820
So one big category of work that
we do is in network analysis.

00:39:43.820 --> 00:39:46.580
Using social media graph data,
the connections between people

00:39:46.580 --> 00:39:49.100
online to understand what
people's interests are,

00:39:49.100 --> 00:39:51.290
to look at who people
are connected to, what

00:39:51.290 --> 00:39:53.900
influencers or celebrities they
follow to get an understanding

00:39:53.900 --> 00:39:56.540
of what type of content they'd
be interested in, what type

00:39:56.540 --> 00:39:59.360
of movies they may want to see.

00:39:59.360 --> 00:40:01.730
Secondly, we do a lot of
work in image recognition

00:40:01.730 --> 00:40:04.100
using exciting relatively
new deep learning

00:40:04.100 --> 00:40:06.290
models, like convolutional
neural network models,

00:40:06.290 --> 00:40:08.690
to take in images as data,
to actually work directly

00:40:08.690 --> 00:40:11.060
on pixel data and
make predictions

00:40:11.060 --> 00:40:13.580
about what those images mean
and what it means for someone

00:40:13.580 --> 00:40:15.110
to have shared them.

00:40:15.110 --> 00:40:16.640
So in particular,
in our industry,

00:40:16.640 --> 00:40:18.390
we're very interested
in people's response

00:40:18.390 --> 00:40:19.280
to visual media.

00:40:19.280 --> 00:40:22.800
If we send a creative message
out as an advertisement,

00:40:22.800 --> 00:40:25.110
what will people respond
to and what types of people

00:40:25.110 --> 00:40:27.230
will respond to each
type of message?

00:40:27.230 --> 00:40:30.260
So for example, from working our
Kong movie, what type of person

00:40:30.260 --> 00:40:32.880
is going to be interested
in seeing Kong himself,

00:40:32.880 --> 00:40:35.840
the actual monster in the
film, versus other aspects

00:40:35.840 --> 00:40:38.830
of the imagery in the film.

00:40:38.830 --> 00:40:40.270
And one more
category of examples

00:40:40.270 --> 00:40:42.250
is a natural
language processing.

00:40:42.250 --> 00:40:45.040
Building models that actually
understand text as people

00:40:45.040 --> 00:40:48.190
write a text and share
messages with each other online

00:40:48.190 --> 00:40:50.290
to understand what those
individuals are actually

00:40:50.290 --> 00:40:53.390
trying to express to their
friends and to others.

00:40:53.390 --> 00:40:55.979
So we use a variety of
approaches for this.

00:40:55.979 --> 00:40:57.520
The example I am
showing you is using

00:40:57.520 --> 00:40:59.870
something called, a
hierarchical attention network.

00:40:59.870 --> 00:41:01.536
This is a type of
model that understands

00:41:01.536 --> 00:41:03.610
not only what it means
to use a particular word,

00:41:03.610 --> 00:41:05.818
but also the context in
which words are used together

00:41:05.818 --> 00:41:07.000
to form sentences.

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:09.190
And very importantly,
what to pay attention to,

00:41:09.190 --> 00:41:12.880
literally to attend
to, within a sentence.

00:41:12.880 --> 00:41:14.620
What words carry
the most meaning

00:41:14.620 --> 00:41:16.390
when someone composes a message.

00:41:16.390 --> 00:41:17.980
And among other things,
we use this type of model

00:41:17.980 --> 00:41:19.438
to predict the
emotions that people

00:41:19.438 --> 00:41:23.710
are trying to express when
they share messages online.

00:41:23.710 --> 00:41:26.809
So I'm sure none of this is a
huge surprise that companies

00:41:26.809 --> 00:41:28.600
are interested in using
predictive modeling

00:41:28.600 --> 00:41:30.640
for purposes like
these, but actually

00:41:30.640 --> 00:41:34.030
have a concern about how data
scientists often projected

00:41:34.030 --> 00:41:35.715
and spoken about in
industry, which is I

00:41:35.715 --> 00:41:37.090
think sometimes,
there's actually

00:41:37.090 --> 00:41:39.370
an over interest
in or over reliance

00:41:39.370 --> 00:41:41.020
on this concept of prediction.

00:41:41.020 --> 00:41:42.580
So I think sometimes
machine learning

00:41:42.580 --> 00:41:45.980
is spoken of as synonymous
with prediction.

00:41:45.980 --> 00:41:47.820
So what I mean is
I think sometimes

00:41:47.820 --> 00:41:49.570
when people think of
the modeling process,

00:41:49.570 --> 00:41:51.640
this is not actually the
picture they have in mind.

00:41:51.640 --> 00:41:52.630
What they have in
mind is something

00:41:52.630 --> 00:41:55.420
more like this, where there
is one element of the modeling

00:41:55.420 --> 00:41:56.862
process that sort of takes over.

00:41:56.862 --> 00:41:59.320
And I think there's at least
one other part of the modeling

00:41:59.320 --> 00:42:02.020
process that's equally
interesting and important,

00:42:02.020 --> 00:42:03.016
and that's inference.

00:42:03.016 --> 00:42:04.390
What I mean by
inference is being

00:42:04.390 --> 00:42:07.072
able to learn from the model
fitting process itself,

00:42:07.072 --> 00:42:09.280
to be able to learn from
the comparison between model

00:42:09.280 --> 00:42:13.610
and data about the process
that we're trying to model.

00:42:13.610 --> 00:42:15.970
So in my sort of definition
of statistical inference

00:42:15.970 --> 00:42:20.329
is the ability to learn from the
comparison of models and data.

00:42:20.329 --> 00:42:22.870
So to make this concrete, let
me give you those same examples

00:42:22.870 --> 00:42:24.800
again, but from an
inference perspective.

00:42:24.800 --> 00:42:27.160
So in science we might want
to ask not just how bright

00:42:27.160 --> 00:42:28.990
is a supernova going
to be, but what

00:42:28.990 --> 00:42:31.847
are the properties of the stars
that led to those explosions.

00:42:31.847 --> 00:42:34.180
And in industry, we want to
know not just whether or not

00:42:34.180 --> 00:42:36.040
someone's going
to go see a movie,

00:42:36.040 --> 00:42:38.167
but what led them to
make that decision.

00:42:38.167 --> 00:42:39.250
What is it about the film?

00:42:39.250 --> 00:42:40.999
What is it about the
person that made them

00:42:40.999 --> 00:42:42.930
interested in that content?

00:42:42.930 --> 00:42:45.900
So ultimately, for-- I think
scientists in both academia

00:42:45.900 --> 00:42:47.890
and in industry,
ultimately, inference

00:42:47.890 --> 00:42:49.070
is a decision making tool.

00:42:49.070 --> 00:42:53.070
It's what allows us to use data
and use data science to inform

00:42:53.070 --> 00:42:55.800
the decisions that we
make as movie producers,

00:42:55.800 --> 00:42:57.600
as executives, and
as scientists trying

00:42:57.600 --> 00:42:59.700
to evaluate different theories.

00:42:59.700 --> 00:43:02.730
So let me give you sort of
another scattering of examples

00:43:02.730 --> 00:43:05.592
of how we apply statistical
inference at Legendary.

00:43:05.592 --> 00:43:07.050
And again, I'll
just kind of survey

00:43:07.050 --> 00:43:08.912
a few different categories.

00:43:08.912 --> 00:43:10.370
So the first category
is inferences

00:43:10.370 --> 00:43:12.690
that we use to understand
content, understand

00:43:12.690 --> 00:43:14.294
the actual products
that we produce.

00:43:14.294 --> 00:43:16.710
And this is another area where
natural language processing

00:43:16.710 --> 00:43:17.912
is very valuable to us.

00:43:17.912 --> 00:43:19.620
So we'll look at the
textual descriptions

00:43:19.620 --> 00:43:23.159
that we have for films that are
generated by users, consumers

00:43:23.159 --> 00:43:25.200
who are discussing them
online, or even generated

00:43:25.200 --> 00:43:26.580
by our own creative team.

00:43:26.580 --> 00:43:29.040
And among other things,
we use a type of model

00:43:29.040 --> 00:43:32.410
called a partially labeled
[INAUDIBLE] allocation model.

00:43:32.410 --> 00:43:35.700
This is a model that can
take a large stream of text

00:43:35.700 --> 00:43:37.860
and decompose it into
fundamental elements.

00:43:37.860 --> 00:43:39.360
And we use this
really to understand

00:43:39.360 --> 00:43:40.980
what are the themes
that are present

00:43:40.980 --> 00:43:42.210
within different movies.

00:43:42.210 --> 00:43:44.850
This allows us to statistically
compare movies to each other.

00:43:44.850 --> 00:43:46.410
Understand how they're
similar and how they're

00:43:46.410 --> 00:43:47.610
different from each other.

00:43:47.610 --> 00:43:49.485
And also, it's useful
for making predictions.

00:43:49.485 --> 00:43:52.380
We can use that same inferences
about thematic content

00:43:52.380 --> 00:43:54.960
to anticipate what types of
themes are going to be popular

00:43:54.960 --> 00:43:58.050
and what types of people
they're going to appeal to.

00:43:58.050 --> 00:44:00.230
We also use inference to
understand market behaviors

00:44:00.230 --> 00:44:01.110
at large.

00:44:01.110 --> 00:44:03.910
So I'll tie this back
specifically to the problem

00:44:03.910 --> 00:44:07.350
that I described of having this
messy and relatively sparse

00:44:07.350 --> 00:44:09.540
data and observing supernovae.

00:44:09.540 --> 00:44:11.860
Actually, in a lot of ways,
Hollywood is very similar.

00:44:11.860 --> 00:44:13.560
So if you look at
any particular genre,

00:44:13.560 --> 00:44:15.570
there's typically only a
few major film releases

00:44:15.570 --> 00:44:17.010
in that genre per year.

00:44:17.010 --> 00:44:20.510
And just like those observations
of the supernova explosion,

00:44:20.510 --> 00:44:22.860
every time another
studio releases a film,

00:44:22.860 --> 00:44:25.110
that's a precious
opportunity for us

00:44:25.110 --> 00:44:27.300
to learn about how the
market is responding

00:44:27.300 --> 00:44:28.660
to that type of product.

00:44:28.660 --> 00:44:31.110
So we invest a lot of time
in building models that

00:44:31.110 --> 00:44:33.690
are sensitive enough and have
a detailed enough accounting

00:44:33.690 --> 00:44:36.300
of uncertainty so that we
can learn as much as possible

00:44:36.300 --> 00:44:39.910
from these relatively
infrequent events.

00:44:39.910 --> 00:44:41.730
And finally, we-- sort
of another category

00:44:41.730 --> 00:44:43.855
is doing inference on
individual consumer behavior.

00:44:43.855 --> 00:44:46.020
So this is our tie back
to Alyssa and her decision

00:44:46.020 --> 00:44:48.189
to go see Pacific Rim,
that's she's going to do.

00:44:48.189 --> 00:44:49.980
And the way we know
she is going to do that

00:44:49.980 --> 00:44:52.740
is that we look at
data from consumers

00:44:52.740 --> 00:44:54.132
that we have information about.

00:44:54.132 --> 00:44:55.590
We know some of
their interests and

00:44:55.590 --> 00:44:57.570
their demographic attributes.

00:44:57.570 --> 00:44:59.911
And we know what messages
that they've been exposed to,

00:44:59.911 --> 00:45:01.410
what advertisements
they've received

00:45:01.410 --> 00:45:03.064
for different films over time.

00:45:03.064 --> 00:45:04.980
And we compare that to
their eventual decision

00:45:04.980 --> 00:45:06.114
to go see a film or not.

00:45:06.114 --> 00:45:07.530
And we learn from
that comparison.

00:45:07.530 --> 00:45:08.904
Where are the
attributes and what

00:45:08.904 --> 00:45:11.160
are the messaging techniques
that actually influence

00:45:11.160 --> 00:45:13.950
people to change and be
persuaded in their opinion

00:45:13.950 --> 00:45:16.860
to go see a film.

00:45:16.860 --> 00:45:18.864
The last aspect of this
I want to talk about

00:45:18.864 --> 00:45:20.280
is one more
fundamental difference

00:45:20.280 --> 00:45:22.920
that I see between prediction
in general and inference

00:45:22.920 --> 00:45:25.590
in general, which is
that a prediction can

00:45:25.590 --> 00:45:28.429
be automated directly
into business processes.

00:45:28.429 --> 00:45:29.970
So of course, we
can build algorithms

00:45:29.970 --> 00:45:32.700
that directly operate on the
output of a predictive model

00:45:32.700 --> 00:45:34.920
without necessarily having
any human involvement,

00:45:34.920 --> 00:45:36.810
without having a
person actually looking

00:45:36.810 --> 00:45:38.220
at the output of that model.

00:45:38.220 --> 00:45:40.110
But in my view, inference
is fundamentally

00:45:40.110 --> 00:45:40.969
different from that.

00:45:40.969 --> 00:45:43.260
So in my view, to actually
extract value from inference

00:45:43.260 --> 00:45:45.660
to benefit from
statistical inference

00:45:45.660 --> 00:45:47.120
we need to have
people in the loop.

00:45:47.120 --> 00:45:48.870
People who are actually
looking at models,

00:45:48.870 --> 00:45:51.064
interpreting them, and
communicating those results

00:45:51.064 --> 00:45:53.730
to other people who are going to
be involved in making decisions

00:45:53.730 --> 00:45:55.420
based on that data.

00:45:55.420 --> 00:45:59.880
So for me this has
profound implications

00:45:59.880 --> 00:46:02.460
for how we prepare scientists
to do this type of work.

00:46:02.460 --> 00:46:04.410
Frankly, whether it's
in academic research

00:46:04.410 --> 00:46:05.580
or in industry.

00:46:05.580 --> 00:46:07.200
So for me, the two
big implications

00:46:07.200 --> 00:46:10.300
are one, what we need to
prepare scientists to do.

00:46:10.300 --> 00:46:13.380
And in my mind, the
critical aspect of this

00:46:13.380 --> 00:46:15.090
is the communication part.

00:46:15.090 --> 00:46:17.579
So this is the way I always
make the argument for why

00:46:17.579 --> 00:46:19.620
communication is a critical
and fundamental skill

00:46:19.620 --> 00:46:20.710
for scientists.

00:46:20.710 --> 00:46:23.070
And it's that you can do
the most amazing research

00:46:23.070 --> 00:46:23.830
imaginable.

00:46:23.830 --> 00:46:25.524
It can be absolutely
groundbreaking.

00:46:25.524 --> 00:46:26.940
It can be rigorous,
sophisticated.

00:46:26.940 --> 00:46:28.050
It can be perfect.

00:46:28.050 --> 00:46:30.457
But if you can't
successfully persuade someone

00:46:30.457 --> 00:46:33.040
to pay attention to what you're
doing, to be interested in it,

00:46:33.040 --> 00:46:34.890
and to have faith that what
we are doing is correct,

00:46:34.890 --> 00:46:36.473
then it may as well
not have happened.

00:46:36.473 --> 00:46:38.470
Your work will have no
impact in the world.

00:46:38.470 --> 00:46:41.070
That's why I think
communication is critical.

00:46:41.070 --> 00:46:43.980
The next question is what a
step in a scientist lifecycle

00:46:43.980 --> 00:46:46.292
should we focus on
building these skills?

00:46:46.292 --> 00:46:48.000
And in my mind, there's
an obvious answer

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:49.470
to that too, which
is that I think

00:46:49.470 --> 00:46:51.630
it has to be at the
graduate student level.

00:46:51.630 --> 00:46:53.650
I think there's two
reasons for this.

00:46:53.650 --> 00:46:55.984
One is that if you ask the
question of who does science,

00:46:55.984 --> 00:46:58.566
if you look at academia and say,
who's the one doing the work?

00:46:58.566 --> 00:46:59.630
It's graduate students.

00:46:59.630 --> 00:47:02.129
The graduate students in general
in the US in different STEM

00:47:02.129 --> 00:47:04.110
fields outnumber,
postdocs outnumber faculty

00:47:04.110 --> 00:47:05.319
by nearly 10 to 1.

00:47:05.319 --> 00:47:07.110
Graduate students are
really the broad base

00:47:07.110 --> 00:47:09.720
of our enterprise of
scientific research.

00:47:09.720 --> 00:47:11.550
And secondly, graduates
since of course

00:47:11.550 --> 00:47:12.924
have made different
career paths.

00:47:12.924 --> 00:47:14.880
Some of them go on into
research and academia.

00:47:14.880 --> 00:47:17.335
Some of them go on into
industry, and many other paths.

00:47:17.335 --> 00:47:18.960
So if we want all
scientists, no matter

00:47:18.960 --> 00:47:21.251
where they're working, to
have this kind of preparation

00:47:21.251 --> 00:47:24.210
and be equipped to communicate
the results of their work,

00:47:24.210 --> 00:47:26.325
I think we have to
target graduate students.

00:47:26.325 --> 00:47:28.200
So the last thing I'll
say is that I'm really

00:47:28.200 --> 00:47:30.491
proud to have been part of
a group of graduate students

00:47:30.491 --> 00:47:31.740
here at Harvard in 2012.

00:47:31.740 --> 00:47:33.240
We founded a program
that's designed

00:47:33.240 --> 00:47:35.940
to equip graduate
students with these skills

00:47:35.940 --> 00:47:37.650
and empower them to
take leadership roles

00:47:37.650 --> 00:47:39.710
and how scientists
communicate to the public.

00:47:39.710 --> 00:47:41.340
And that's an organization
called ComSciCon,

00:47:41.340 --> 00:47:42.840
the Communicating
Science Conference

00:47:42.840 --> 00:47:44.970
here that Alyssa kindly
alluded to earlier.

00:47:44.970 --> 00:47:48.109
We also are fortunate to have
one of the leaders of ComSciCon

00:47:48.109 --> 00:47:50.400
in the audience, Ben Cook,
who is an astronomy graduate

00:47:50.400 --> 00:47:52.524
student here and leads
ComSciCon's local organizing

00:47:52.524 --> 00:47:53.439
committee.

00:47:53.439 --> 00:47:55.230
And ComSciCon really
does two things today.

00:47:55.230 --> 00:47:57.438
We have a national workshop
on leadership and science

00:47:57.438 --> 00:47:59.170
communication for
graduate students,

00:47:59.170 --> 00:48:01.710
and we have a network of
ComSciCon franchises operated

00:48:01.710 --> 00:48:03.960
by our student alums
throughout the country who

00:48:03.960 --> 00:48:06.050
are spreading the work
that we do even further.

00:48:06.050 --> 00:48:07.500
And if you're
interested, like me,

00:48:07.500 --> 00:48:10.280
in how scientists are prepared
to communicate with the public,

00:48:10.280 --> 00:48:12.613
and if you're interested in
supporting graduate students

00:48:12.613 --> 00:48:14.760
in doing this work, please
check out ComSciCon.com,

00:48:14.760 --> 00:48:17.330
and please feel free to ask
me questions about it as well.

00:48:17.330 --> 00:48:17.968
Thank you.

